            "accordion_row_seo1": {
              "type": "_accordion-row",
              "name": "t:names.accordion_dash_row",
              "settings": {
                "heading": "Is VG10 steel better than German steel?",
                "content": "<p>VG10 achieves 60-61 HRC compared to 56-58 HRC for typical German steels. This means it holds a sharper edge significantly longer. However, it's slightly more brittle and requires a whetstone rather than a pull-through sharpener. For cooks who want maximum sharpness and don't mind careful maintenance, VG10 is the better choice. See our <a href=\"/blogs/news/knife-steel-hardness-guide\">steel hardness guide</a> for more detail.</p>",
                "open_by_default": false,
                "icon": "none",
                "width": 20
              },
              "blocks": {
                "text_qyicfu": {
                  "type": "text",
                  "name": "t:names.text",
                  "settings": {
                    "text": "<p>VG10 achieves 60-61 HRC compared to 56-58 HRC for typical German steels. This means it holds a sharper edge significantly longer. However, it's slightly more brittle and requires a whetstone rather than a pull-through sharpener. For cooks who want maximum sharpness and don't mind careful maintenance, VG10 is the better choice. See our <a href=\"/blogs/news/knife-steel-hardness-guide\">steel hardness guide</a> for more detail.</p>",
